english:
  title: An Edict Bestowing the Posthumous Title of Perfect and Wondrous National Master upon Yoose, the Abbot of the White Lotus Society at Mandok Mountain
  author: Min In-gyun
  language: eng
  text: 'By edict it is declared: Extraordinary honors must follow extraordinary virtue. For more than three centuries, our realm has elevated great monks to the rank of National Master—only such luminaries as Great Awakening, Unobstructed Wisdom, Universal Illumination, and True Enlightenment have received such distinction. But in later times, there arose one whose exceptional merit prevented even his predecessors from monopolizing glory—our own revered teacher. With abundant spiritual gifts and commanding presence, he arose to meet the age, raising high the banner of the dharma and striking the drum of the law. His work in propagating the teachings and benefiting all people shines brilliantly, vying with sun and moon for luminescence. Why would we hesitate to bestow honor upon such a one? We now confer upon him the title of the Perfect and Wondrous National Master.'
  footnotes:
    - The four great monks mentioned—Great Awakening (Dae-gak), Unobstructed Wisdom (Mu-ae-ji), Universal Illumination (Bo-jo), and True Enlightenment (Jin-gak)—represent the most illustrious Buddhist leaders in Korean history who received the title of National Master.
    - The metaphor of raising the dharma banner and striking the dharma drum are traditional Buddhist images representing the active teaching and transmission of Buddhist doctrine.
